The plant had long, thin, gray, fuzzy, and serrated leaves that looked exactly like yerba santa. This species is the only resident of the Yosemite Valley, this one growing in the disturbed portion of the Mountain Meadow.

The fern was abundant in the mossy regions of the rock outcrops, it has a very triangular form, not as branched out as the brackern. The stems were also long and fresh. It grew down low in the Lower Montane Forest.

The tree was an evergreen with gray, sprawling branches. The leaves were shiny, smooth, and had fragrance to them. A glaze of water coated the leaves due to the close proximity of the Brivadel Falls. It grew in the moist Lower Montane Forest.

This manzanita species is abundant in the Sierras. The leaves are large, bold green ovals. The stems were slick, red, and woody. The flowers were soft whites and pinks. This grew next to an old snag in the Lower Montane Forest.

ID seemed obvious as I watched it continue under the bridge. Then it went up the bank where there was an opening in the vegetation. The bank was mostly steep and woody in its path along the river. I lost sight of the otter when it went up the bank and didn't see it after watching the area awhile. Later I searched the area where I had seen the otter disappear up the bank and found fresh disturbance in the partly sandy soil next to the river. The photos are of area.
